sentence: The Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJI) witnessed another triple-digit swing today, as a few major headlines hit the Street.
"Last night, Google was the big story.
But that was quickly overshadowed by China's worse-than-expected GDP, and concerns over rising Spanish bond yields," said Senior Equity Analyst Joe Bell.
"Concerns about the pace of global growth sent shares down for the day."

Keep reading to see what else was on our radar today:
• How much did China really contribute to today's selloff?
• See how Google ( GOOG ) and JPMorgan ( JPM ) fared after earnings.
• The latest sentiment survey showed a surprising shift among active money managers last week.
• Plus, Bell discussed which regional banks are besting their multi-national counterparts .
And now, a look at the numbers...
The Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJI - 12,849.59) slouched nearly 137 points, or 1.1%, today, tagging a session low of 12,845.28 just before the closing bell.
All but two of the 30 components closed with losses, as Bank of America ( BAC ) paced the 28 laggards with a 5.3% slide.
Home Depot ( HD ) and Kraft Foods ( KFT ) inched up 0.7% and 0.6%, respectively.
The blue chip barometer lopped off 1.6% for the week.
The S&P 500 Index (SPX - 1,370.26) peeled away from the 1,375 mark , and gave back 17.3 points, or 1.3%.
Meanwhile, the Nasdaq Composite (COMP - 3,011.33) fared the worst of its fellow benchmarks, and sawed off 44.2 points, or 1.5%.
The SPX ended the week with a 2% drop, while the COMP suffered a 2.2% deficit.
The CBOE Market Volatility Index (VIX - 19.55) was up today, jumping 13.7% to land near its session peak of 19.62.
The market's fear gauge increased by 17.1% on the week.
Today's highlight : "Despite the headlines about China's scary GDP , actual Chinese companies somehow survive the day unscathed," highlighted Bell.
"Youku (YOKU) and E-Commerce China Dangdang (DANG) are two examples of stocks that outperformed the broad market.
DANG was even downgraded this morning and still finished in the green.
Apparently, the global slowdown concern from China's GDP isn't going to actually affect companies doing business in China ."
The latest survey from the National Association of Active Investment Managers (NAAIM) showed that money managers dramatically slashed their exposure to equities last week.
Click here to read more.
• U.S. Bancorp (USB) has popped up as a regional bank to keep an eye on.
• Both Google ( GOOG ) and JPMorgan Chase ( JPM ) took a dive after unveiling their first-quarter earnings reports .
• Bearish opportunities arose in the oil patch on Transocean (RIG), Halliburton (HAL), and Talisman Energy (TLM).
• An options trader rolled down his short calls on Hewlett-Packard (HPQ).
• Macquarie is "positive" on global oil-weighted producers, but slashed its price target on Southwestern Energy (SWN) .
For today's activity in commodities, options, and more, head to page 2.
Crude futures couldn't keep their positive momentum going today, as traders worried about the impact of a slowing Chinese economy on global demand.
May-dated oil dropped 81 cents, or 0.8%, to settle at $102.83 a barrel.
Oil slipped 0.5% throughout the week.
